imal;"><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Media scrum for next season</em=
>: Super Bowl week has always doubled as a <em>de facto</em> trade show for=
 the sports business=E2=80=94a place where media and sponsorship executives=
 lobby the NFL honchos for, among other things, the best games on next year=
=E2=80=99s schedule. This year, however, the league is holding most of its =
network meetings <em>before</em> they get to New Orleans. (Network lobbying=
 will continue, of course, right up to the moment the schedule is released =
in
the spring.)<br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s easy to identify the games the networks =
most covet: anything involving the Chiefs and (yes, still) the Cowboys. Nex=
t season=E2=80=99s blockbusters include an AFC Championship rematch (Chiefs=
 at Bills) and a Super Bowl rematch (Eagles at Chiefs). Another highly priz=
ed game will be Kansas City at Dallas. Both the Chiefs and Cowboys also pla=
y the Lions=E2=80=94those are games that every network would want to carry.=
<br/><br/>Christmas Day, which falls on a Thursday this year, also poses an
interesting question. Amazon Prime is a few years into a decade-plus deal p=
aying about $1 billion per year to broadcast <em>Thursday Night Football</e=
m>, while Netflix has a three-year deal to carry games on Christmas for a f=
ew hundred million bucks a pop. The NFL <em>could </em>schedule a triple-he=
ader, with Netflix carrying two afternoon games and Amazon carrying one at =
night. But which streamer would get the best game and window? We=E2=80=99ll=
 see=E2=80=A6 Meanwhile, media executives will also be
probing the league for guidance on extending the regular season and the gro=
wth of the league=E2=80=99s international schedule, since <strong>Roger Goo=
dell </strong>has publicly stated he wants to expand both.</li><li style=3D=
"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Is there really Chiefs fatigue?</em>: Don=E2=80=99=
t believe anything you read about the possibility of =E2=80=9CChiefs fatigu=
e=E2=80=9D diminishing the Super Bowl broadcast viewership. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s a social media creation,=E2=80=9D said one media executive, who lau=
ghed off any suggestion that
people might not watch the Super Bowl because they=E2=80=99re tired of seei=
ng <strong>Patrick Mahomes</strong> win all the time, or because they=E2=80=
=99re fed up with the <strong>Taylor</strong>=E2=80=93<strong>Travis</stron=
g> sideshow. Other sports business executives had similar responses.<br/><b=
r/>Networks habitually crunch numbers to determine which NFL team is the mo=
st popular. This season, the Bills and the Lions entered that conversation,=
 but neither got <em>close</em> to matching the Chiefs. =E2=80=9CTo me, the=
 idea of
viewer fatigue is simply teams that turn from being seen as the <em>good gu=
y</em> to being seen as the <em>bad guy</em>,=E2=80=9D another executive to=
ld me. =E2=80=9CEverybody seemed to love the Chiefs a couple of years ago. =
Now, there=E2=80=99s going to be a higher percentage of people hate-watchin=
g to root against them.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Two years ago, the Chiefs and Eag=
les set a Super Bowl record with more than 114 million viewers. Last year=
=E2=80=99s Chiefs-49ers overtime game broke that mark with more than 120 mi=
llion. This year=E2=80=99s
numbers are hard to predict, but they=E2=80=99ll likely be even higher: Fox=
 will stream the game on Tubi, and the network brokered a deal with NBCUniv=
ersal to have Telemundo carry a Spanish-language feed. Meanwhile, Nielsen e=
xpanded its out-of-home coverage, which should allow the game to post big n=
umbers.</li><li aria-level=3D"1" style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Greg Olse=
n=E2=80=99s options</em>: I=E2=80=99ve received emails from Varsity subscri=
bers who are curious about <strong>Greg Olsen</strong>=E2=80=99s future in =
the
broadcast booth. Now that Tom Brady has said that he <em>will</em> return t=
o the Fox booth next season, what happens to the analyst who used to have t=
hat job and now holds up Fox=E2=80=99s number two booth?<br/><br/>The quick=
 answer is that Olsen doesn=E2=80=99t have a lot of options if he wants to =
become a network=E2=80=99s number one analyst. <strong>Cris Collinsworth </=
strong>signed an extension that keeps him on NBC=E2=80=99s <em>Sunday Night=
 Football</em> until the end of the decade. <strong>Troy Aikman</strong>,
<strong>Tony Romo</strong>, and <strong>Kirk Herbstreit</strong> still have=
 multiple years left on their deals. Unless the NFL expands and creates a n=
ew package, there=E2=80=99s nowhere for Olsen to go.</li><li aria-level=3D"=
1" style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Robot refs</em>: Did <strong>Josh Allen=
</strong> extend forward enough to make a first down on that critical fourt=
h-and-one play yesterday? CBS rules analyst <strong>Gene Steratore</strong>=
 sure thought so. The officials on the field disagreed, a
decision that spiked the Bills=E2=80=99 comeback hopes and played a signifi=
cant role in ending their season. That decision, itself, underscored the co=
mplaint that the NFL=E2=80=94a multi-<em>multi-</em>billion-dollar business=
=E2=80=94still relies on referees and a 10-yard chain link to determine the=
 most important plays in the game. If tennis can use Hawk-Eye technology an=
d baseball has dopey robot umpires (sorry, =E2=80=9Cautomated strike zones=
=E2=80=9D), why can=E2=80=99t the NFL put a microchip in the ball to be mor=
e <em>precise</em> about
where, <em>exactly</em>, to start each play?<br/><br/>Putting aside the tec=
hnical question of whether it=E2=80=99s feasible (<strong>Joe Lemire </stro=
ng><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2U=
ktxclJLZ0dVcW9scVNnZDdsZE5ia1lXVDZROD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc3BvcnRz=
YnVzaW5lc3Nqb3VybmFsLmNvbS9BcnRpY2xlcy8yMDI1LzAxLzI3L2hhd2tleWUtbmZsLWZpcnN=
0LWRvd24tY2hpZWZzLWJpbGxzP3B1YmxpY2F0aW9uU291cmNlPXNiZFx1MDAyNmlzc3VlPTkyNz=
